==French==

===Etymology===
From {{inh|fr|fro|ogre}}, from {{inh|fr|la|Orcus||the underworld; the god Pluto}}, with {{glossary|metathesis}}. According to the ''Trésor de la langue française informatisé'', first attested in the late 12th century meaning 'fierce non-Christian', and ca. 1300 meaning 'human-eating giant' (in fairy tales). Cognate with {{cog|osp|huerco||the Devil}}, {{cog|es|huerco||depressed man in the dark}}, {{cog|it|orco||ogre, orc}}.

See also {{noncog|fr|lutin||imp, pixie}}, possibly from {{noncog|fro|netun||marine monster}}, derived from {{m+|la|Neptūnus}}, and also {{noncog|fro|gene||mischievous fairy}} and {{noncog|ro|zână||fairy}}, both derived from {{m+|la|Diana}}. A sermon by [[Merovingian]] French bishop [[w:Saint Eligius|St. Eligius]] (died 659) advises people against belief in Neptune, Diana, Orcus and [[Minerva]].

